[49m[39m    1,   1[0m:[39m[49m # Recipe 7.6: Rising Risk Identification
[0m[49m[39m    2,   2[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m    3,   3[0m:[39m[49m **Complexity:** Medium-Complex · **Phase:** Growth · **Estimated Cost:** ~$0.01 per patient per scoring cycle
[0m[49m[39m    4,   4[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m    5,   5[0m:[39m[49m ---
[0m[49m[39m    6,   6[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m    7,   7[0m:[39m[49m ## The Problem
[0m[49m[39m    8,   8[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m    9,   9[0m:[39m[49m Every health system has a list of high-risk patients. The sickest 5% of the population drives 50% of the cost. Care management teams know who these people are. They have names, diagnoses, care plans, and dedicated nurses assigned to them.
[0m[49m[39m   10,  10[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   11,  11[0m:[39m[49m The problem is not identifying who is already high-risk. The problem is identifying who is *becoming* high-risk.
[0m[49m[39m   12,  12[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   13,  13[0m:[39m[49m By the time a patient shows up on the high-cost list, the window for cost-effective intervention has usually closed. They've already had the hospitalization, the ED visit, the crisis event that pushed them over the threshold. The care management team inherits them after the damage is done, and the interventions available at that point are expensive, reactive, and often too late to change the trajectory.
[0m[49m[39m   14,  14[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   15,  15[0m:[39m[49m Rising risk identification flips the timing. Instead of asking "who is sick right now?" you ask "who is getting sicker?" Instead of a point-in-time snapshot, you're looking at the slope of the line. A patient with well-controlled diabetes whose A1c has crept from 7.2 to 8.1 to 9.4 over three visits is not yet "high-risk" by most static scoring systems. But the trajectory is unmistakable. In six months, without intervention, they'll be in the ED with diabetic ketoacidosis.
[0m[49m[39m   16,  16[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   17,  17[0m:[39m[49m This is the fundamental insight: the rate of change in risk is more actionable than the absolute level of risk. A patient at 60th percentile risk who was at 30th percentile six months ago is a better intervention target than a patient who has been stable at 80th percentile for three years. The first patient is deteriorating and might respond to intervention. The second patient is chronically complex but stable, and their care plan is probably already optimized.
[0m[49m[39m   18,  18[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   19,  19[0m:[39m[49m Health plans and ACOs care about this intensely because of the economics. Intervening on a rising-risk patient before they cross into high-cost territory costs maybe $2,000-5,000 in care management resources. Letting them cross that threshold costs $50,000-100,000 in acute care. The ROI math is compelling, but only if you can identify the right patients early enough for the intervention to matter.
[0m[49m[39m   20,  20[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   21,  21[0m:[39m[49m The challenge: this is a fundamentally harder prediction problem than static risk scoring. You're not just predicting an outcome. You're predicting a change in trajectory. That requires longitudinal data, temporal modeling, and a clear definition of what "rising" actually means in quantitative terms.
[0m[49m[39m   22,  22[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   23,  23[0m:[39m[49m ---
[0m[49m[39m   24,  24[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   25,  25[0m:[39m[49m ## The Technology: Detecting Trajectory Changes
[0m[49m[39m   26,  26[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   27,  27[0m:[39m[49m ### Why Static Risk Scores Miss This
[0m[49m[39m   28,  28[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   29,  29[0m:[39m[49m Traditional risk scoring (HCC-based risk adjustment, LACE scores, Charlson comorbidity indices) produces a point-in-time estimate. It answers: "Given everything we know about this patient right now, what is their expected cost or utilization?" These scores are useful for population stratification, but they have a structural blind spot: they don't model change over time.
[0m[49m[39m   30,  30[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   31,  31[0m:[39m[49m Consider two patients, both with a current HCC risk score of 1.8 (meaning expected cost is 1.8x the average). Patient A has been at 1.8 for three years. Patient B was at 0.9 twelve months ago and has climbed steadily to 1.8. Static scoring treats them identically. But operationally, they're completely different situations. Patient A is stable and probably already in a care management program. Patient B is deteriorating rapidly and may not be on anyone's radar yet.
[0m[49m[39m   32,  32[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   33,  33[0m:[39m[49m Rising risk identification requires temporal awareness. You need to track risk over time and detect meaningful acceleration.
[0m[49m[39m   34,  34[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   35,  35[0m:[39m[49m ### Defining "Rising Risk" Mathematically
[0m[49m[39m   36,  36[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   37,  37[0m:[39m[49m This is where it gets interesting, because "rising risk" is not a single well-defined concept. There are several reasonable definitions, and the right one depends on your intervention model:
[0m[49m[39m   38,  38[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   39,  39[0m:[39m[49m **Absolute change.** The simplest: risk score increased by more than X points over Y months. Easy to compute, easy to explain. But it treats a change from 0.5 to 0.8 the same as a change from 2.0 to 2.3, even though the clinical implications are very different.
[0m[49m[39m   40,  40[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   41,  41[0m:[39m[49m **Relative change.** Risk score increased by more than X% over Y months. Better at capturing proportional deterioration. A 50% increase from 0.6 to 0.9 is arguably more alarming than a 15% increase from 2.0 to 2.3. But relative change can be noisy for patients with very low baseline scores (a change from 0.1 to 0.2 is a 100% increase but clinically meaningless).
[0m[49m[39m   42,  42[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   43,  43[0m:[39m[49m **Percentile migration.** The patient moved from one risk tier to a higher one (e.g., from the 40th to the 70th percentile of the population). This is intuitive for care managers because it maps directly to their stratification tiers. But it depends on the population distribution, which shifts over time.
[0m[49m[39m   44,  44[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   45,  45[0m:[39m[49m **Slope of the trajectory.** Fit a line (or curve) to the patient's risk scores over multiple time points and use the slope as the "rising" indicator. This is the most statistically rigorous approach because it uses all available history, not just two endpoints. It's also more robust to noise: a single anomalous score won't trigger a false alarm if the overall trend is flat.
[0m[49m[39m   46,  46[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   47,  47[0m:[39m[49m **Predicted future state.** Train a model to predict what the patient's risk score will be in 6-12 months, then flag patients whose predicted future score crosses a threshold. This is the most sophisticated approach but also the most complex to build and validate.
[0m[49m[39m   48,  48[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   49,  49[0m:[39m[49m In practice, most production systems use a combination: slope-based detection for the primary signal, with absolute thresholds as guardrails (don't flag someone whose risk is rising but still very low in absolute terms).
[0m[49m[39m   50,  50[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   51,  51[0m:[39m[49m ### The Longitudinal Modeling Challenge
[0m[49m[39m   52,  52[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   53,  53[0m:[39m[49m Rising risk detection requires multiple observations per patient over time. This creates several technical challenges that don't exist in point-in-time prediction:
[0m[49m[39m   54,  54[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   55,  55[0m:[39m[49m **Irregular observation intervals.** Patients don't visit on a fixed schedule. One patient might have monthly lab draws; another might go a year between visits. You can't simply compare "this month's score" to "last month's score" because the time gaps vary wildly. Your model needs to handle irregular time series gracefully, either by interpolating to fixed intervals or by using methods that natively handle irregular spacing.
[0m[49m[39m   56,  56[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   57,  57[0m:[39m[49m **Informative missingness.** A patient who stops showing up for appointments is not "missing data" in the traditional sense. The absence itself is informative. Patients who disengage from care often do so because they're getting sicker (too sick to come in, lost transportation, gave up). If your model only scores patients when new data arrives, you'll systematically miss the ones who are deteriorating silently. You need a mechanism to flag patients whose data has gone stale.
[0m[49m[39m   58,  58[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   59,  59[0m:[39m[49m **Confounding events.** A patient's risk score might jump because they received a new diagnosis that was actually present for years but only recently documented. That's not true clinical deterioration; it's documentation catch-up. Similarly, a patient transitioning from one insurance plan to another might have their claims history reset, creating an artificial trajectory change. Your model needs to distinguish genuine clinical deterioration from data artifacts.
[0m[49m[39m   60,  60[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   61,  61[0m:[39m[49m **Regression to the mean.** Patients identified as "rising risk" based on recent score increases will, on average, partially revert even without intervention. This is a statistical phenomenon, not a clinical one. It makes it genuinely hard to measure whether your interventions are working, because some of the "improvement" you observe would have happened anyway. Proper evaluation requires a control group or at minimum a regression-adjusted comparison.
[0m[49m[39m   62,  62[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   63,  63[0m:[39m[49m <!-- TODO (TechWriter): Expert review A1 (HIGH). Add subsection "Equity and Bias Considerations" after this paragraph. Cover: differential data density (sparse-visit patients fall into INSUFFICIENT_HISTORY), inherited model bias (Obermeyer et al. 2019), threshold equity across demographic groups, and intervention allocation fairness. Include mitigation strategies: audit flag rates by demographic group, group-specific threshold calibration, proactive outreach for sparse-data patients, equity reporting for the insufficient-history population. -->
[0m[49m[39m   64,  64[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   65,  65[0m:[39m[49m ### Feature Engineering for Trajectory Detection
[0m[49m[39m   66,  66[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   67,  67[0m:[39m[49m The features that predict rising risk are different from those that predict current risk. You need both levels and changes:
[0m[49m[39m   68,  68[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   69,  69[0m:[39m[49m **Score deltas.** Change in risk score over 3, 6, and 12-month windows. Both absolute and relative. The multi-window approach captures both rapid deterioration (3-month spike) and slow drift (12-month gradual increase).
[0m[49m[39m   70,  70[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   71,  71[0m:[39m[49m **Utilization acceleration.** Not just "how many ED visits" but "are ED visits increasing?" A patient who went from 0 ED visits in Q1 to 1 in Q2 to 3 in Q3 is on a concerning trajectory even if their total count isn't alarming yet.
[0m[49m[39m   72,  72[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   73,  73[0m:[39m[49m **Clinical marker trends.** Lab values trending in the wrong direction: rising A1c, declining eGFR, increasing BNP. These are leading indicators that often precede acute events by months. The slope of the lab trend is more predictive than the current value for rising risk detection.
[0m[49m[39m   74,  74[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   75,  75[0m:[39m[49m **Care engagement changes.** Missed appointments increasing, medication refill gaps widening, time since last PCP visit growing. Disengagement from care is both a risk factor and a detectable signal.
[0m[49m[39m   76,  76[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   77,  77[0m:[39m[49m **New diagnosis velocity.** The rate at which new chronic conditions are being added. A patient who picks up three new diagnoses in six months is on a different trajectory than one who has been stable for years.
[0m[49m[39m   78,  78[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   79,  79[0m:[39m[49m **Social determinant shifts.** When available: address changes (especially to higher-deprivation areas), insurance coverage gaps, loss of caregiver support. These are powerful predictors but rarely captured in structured data.
[0m[49m[39m   80,  80[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   81,  81[0m:[39m[49m ### Model Architecture Options
[0m[49m[39m   82,  82[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   83,  83[0m:[39m[49m **Sequential risk scoring with delta analysis.** The simplest approach: run your existing point-in-time risk model on a regular schedule (monthly or quarterly), store the scores, and compute deltas. Flag patients whose delta exceeds a threshold. This requires no new model training; it just adds a temporal layer on top of your existing risk stratification. The downside: it only captures what your existing model measures, and it's sensitive to model version changes (if you retrain the underlying model, all deltas become meaningless until the new scores stabilize).
[0m[49m[39m   84,  84[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   85,  85[0m:[39m[49m **Dedicated trajectory model.** Train a separate model specifically to predict risk acceleration. The target variable is not "will this patient be high-cost?" but "will this patient's cost increase by more than X% in the next 12 months?" This model can use trajectory features (slopes, deltas, acceleration) as first-class inputs rather than bolting them on after the fact. It typically outperforms the delta approach but requires more engineering and a separate training pipeline.
[0m[49m[39m   86,  86[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   87,  87[0m:[39m[49m **Recurrent or sequence models.** Use the full sequence of a patient's clinical events (encounters, diagnoses, labs, medications) as input to a recurrent neural network or transformer. These models can learn complex temporal patterns without explicit feature engineering. They're powerful but require large datasets, significant compute, and are harder to interpret. For most health systems, gradient boosting on engineered trajectory features is the practical choice.
[0m[49m[39m   88,  88[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   89,  89[0m:[39m[49m **Survival analysis with time-varying covariates.** Model the time until a patient transitions from low/medium risk to high risk, with covariates that update over time. Cox proportional hazards with time-varying covariates or discrete-time survival models can capture the dynamics naturally. This framing is particularly useful when you care about *when* the transition will happen, not just *whether* it will.
[0m[49m[39m   90,  90[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   91,  91[0m:[39m[49m ### Intervention Timing: The Optimization Problem
[0m[49m[39m   92,  92[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   93,  93[0m:[39m[49m Identifying rising-risk patients is only half the problem. The other half is deciding when to intervene. Too early, and you're spending resources on patients who might have stabilized on their own. Too late, and the intervention can't change the trajectory. The optimal intervention point depends on:
[0m[49m[39m   94,  94[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   95,  95[0m:[39m[49m **Intervention lead time.** How long does it take for the intervention to have an effect? A care management enrollment might take 2-4 weeks to produce measurable behavior change. If you wait until the patient is 30 days from a hospitalization, you've missed the window.
[0m[49m[39m   96,  96[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   97,  97[0m:[39m[49m **Trajectory confidence.** How many data points do you need before you're confident the trend is real and not noise? Two consecutive score increases might be random variation. Four consecutive increases over 12 months is a pattern. There's a tension between acting early (when you have less certainty) and acting late (when you have more certainty but less time).
[0m[49m[39m   98,  98[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   99,  99[0m:[39m[49m **Intervention capacity.** Your care management team can handle N new enrollments per month. If your model flags 500 patients but you can only serve 50, you need to prioritize. The prioritization should consider both the severity of the trajectory and the likelihood that intervention will change it.
[0m[49m[39m  100, 100[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  101, 101[0m:[39m[49m ---
[0m[49m[39m  102, 102[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  103, 103[0m:[39m[49m ## General Architecture Pattern
[0m[49m[39m  104, 104[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  105, 105[0m:[39m[49m The rising risk pipeline operates on a different cadence than real-time scoring. It's a batch process that runs periodically (weekly or monthly), compares current state to historical state, and produces a ranked list of patients whose trajectories warrant attention.
[0m[49m[39m  106, 106[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  107, 107[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  108, 108[0m:[39m[49m [Periodic Risk Scoring] → [Score History Storage] → [Trajectory Computation] → [Rising Risk Detection] → [Prioritization & Routing]
[0m[49m[39m  109, 109[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  110, 110[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  111, 111[0m:[39m[49m **Periodic Risk Scoring.** On a regular schedule, compute risk scores for the entire managed population. This might use an existing risk model (HCC, proprietary, or custom ML) or a purpose-built trajectory model. The key requirement is consistency: the same model version must be used across scoring cycles, or score comparisons become meaningless.
[0m[49m[39m  112, 112[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  113, 113[0m:[39m[49m <!-- TODO (TechWriter): Expert review A3 (MEDIUM). Add note about pipeline failure monitoring: recommend Step Functions or equivalent orchestrator with error handling. Each step should emit success/failure metrics to CloudWatch. Configure alarms for: pipeline not completing within expected window, any step failure, anomalous output (flagged count deviating >50% from prior cycle). Alert ops team if pipeline fails, since a missed cycle means rising-risk patients go unidentified for an additional month. -->
[0m[49m[39m  114, 114[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  115, 115[0m:[39m[49m **Score History Storage.** Every scoring cycle's results are stored with timestamps, creating a longitudinal record of each patient's risk trajectory. This is a time-series storage problem: millions of patients, each with a score at each cycle, potentially going back years. The storage must support efficient queries like "give me all scores for patient X over the last 24 months" and "give me all patients whose most recent score exceeds their score from 6 months ago by more than 0.5."
[0m[49m[39m  116, 116[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  117, 117[0m:[39m[49m **Trajectory Computation.** For each patient, compute trajectory metrics: slope over multiple windows, acceleration (change in slope), percentile migration, and time since last significant change. This is computationally intensive at population scale but embarrassingly parallel (each patient's trajectory is independent).
[0m[49m[39m  118, 118[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  119, 119[0m:[39m[49m **Rising Risk Detection.** Apply detection rules or a trained model to the trajectory metrics to identify patients whose risk is meaningfully increasing. This produces a candidate list with associated confidence scores and trajectory summaries.
[0m[49m[39m  120, 120[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  121, 121[0m:[39m[49m **Prioritization and Routing.** Rank the candidates by intervention urgency and likelihood of benefit. Route to the appropriate care management program based on the nature of the risk increase (behavioral health escalation goes to BH care managers; chronic disease acceleration goes to disease management; social determinant deterioration goes to community health workers).
[0m[49m[39m  122, 122[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  123, 123[0m:[39m[49m ---
[0m[49m[39m  124, 124[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  125, 125[0m:[39m[49m ## The AWS Implementation
[0m[49m[39m  126, 126[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  127, 127[0m:[39m[49m ### Why These Services
[0m[49m[39m  128, 128[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  129, 129[0m:[39m[49m **Amazon SageMaker for model training and batch inference.** Rising risk scoring is a batch workload: you're scoring an entire population on a schedule, not responding to real-time events. SageMaker's batch transform jobs are purpose-built for this. You upload your feature matrix, point it at your trained model, and get back scored results for millions of patients without managing any infrastructure. For model training, SageMaker's managed training jobs handle the compute scaling and experiment tracking.
[0m[49m[39m  130, 130[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  131, 131[0m:[39m[49m **Amazon S3 for score history and feature storage.** The longitudinal score history is a growing dataset (new scores every cycle, retained indefinitely). S3 with a partitioned structure (by scoring date) gives you cheap, durable storage with efficient access patterns for both "get one patient's history" and "get all patients from one cycle." Parquet format keeps storage costs low and query performance high.
[0m[49m[39m  132, 132[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  133, 133[0m:[39m[49m **AWS Glue for feature engineering and trajectory computation.** The trajectory computation step (computing slopes, deltas, and acceleration for millions of patients) is a distributed data processing job. Glue's Spark-based engine handles the scale, and the serverless model means you're not paying for idle compute between scoring cycles. Glue also handles the ETL from source systems (EHR extracts, claims feeds) into the feature store.
[0m[49m[39m  134, 134[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  135, 135[0m:[39m[49m **Amazon DynamoDB for operational risk state.** The current risk tier, trajectory status, and intervention routing for each patient needs to be available in real-time for care management workflows. DynamoDB provides single-digit-millisecond lookups by patient ID, which is what the care management platform needs when a nurse opens a patient's record.
[0m[49m[39m  136, 136[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  137, 137[0m:[39m[49m <!-- TODO (TechWriter): Expert review S1 (HIGH). Add paragraph on access control: API layer with panel-level authorization mediating DynamoDB access, Lambda authorizer validating panel assignment, restricting direct DynamoDB access to pipeline IAM roles only. HIPAA minimum-necessary standard requires care managers access only attributed patients. -->
[0m[49m[39m  138, 138[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  139, 139[0m:[39m[49m **Amazon EventBridge for orchestration.** The scoring pipeline runs on a schedule (weekly or monthly). EventBridge Scheduler triggers the pipeline, and EventBridge rules route completion events to downstream consumers (notifications to care managers, updates to the care management platform, alerts for rapid deterioration).
[0m[49m[39m  140, 140[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  141, 141[0m:[39m[49m <!-- TODO (TechWriter): Expert review S2 (MEDIUM). Add note: SNS notifications with patient IDs and trajectory data are PHI. Restrict subscriptions to HIPAA-compliant endpoints (SQS, Lambda, HTTPS). Avoid email/SMS with clinical details. Send minimal alerts with dashboard links instead of embedding trajectory data in notification body. -->
[0m[49m[39m  142, 142[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  143, 143[0m:[39m[49m **Amazon QuickSight for population-level dashboards.** Leadership needs to see the rising risk population in aggregate: how many patients are flagged, what's the distribution of trajectory severity, which programs are at capacity. QuickSight can query the S3 score history directly, so you don't need to stand up a separate data warehouse just for leadership dashboards.
[0m[49m[39m  144, 144[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  145, 145[0m:[39m[49m ### Architecture Diagram
[0m[49m[39m  146, 146[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  147, 147[0m:[39m[49m ```mermaid
[0m[49m[39m  148, 148[0m:[39m[49m flowchart TD
[0m[49m[39m  149, 149[0m:[39m[49m     A[EventBridge Scheduler\nWeekly/Monthly Trigger] --> B[AWS Glue Job\nFeature Assembly]
[0m[49m[39m  150, 150[0m:[39m[49m     B --> C[S3\nFeature Store\nParquet partitioned by date]
[0m[49m[39m  151, 151[0m:[39m[49m     C --> D[SageMaker Batch Transform\nRisk Scoring]
[0m[49m[39m  152, 152[0m:[39m[49m     D --> E[S3\nScore History\nAppend new cycle]
[0m[49m[39m  153, 153[0m:[39m[49m     E --> F[AWS Glue Job\nTrajectory Computation]
[0m[49m[39m  154, 154[0m:[39m[49m     F --> G[S3\nTrajectory Results\nSlopes, deltas, flags]
[0m[49m[39m  155, 155[0m:[39m[49m     G --> H[Lambda\nRising Risk Detection\n& Prioritization]
[0m[49m[39m  156, 156[0m:[39m[49m     H --> I[DynamoDB\nPatient Risk State\nCurrent tier + trajectory]
[0m[49m[39m  157, 157[0m:[39m[49m     H --> J[EventBridge\nAlert Events]
[0m[49m[39m  158, 158[0m:[39m[49m     J --> K[SNS\nCare Manager Notifications]
[0m[49m[39m  159, 159[0m:[39m[49m     I --> L[Care Management Platform\nAPI Integration]
[0m[49m[39m  160, 160[0m:[39m[49m     E --> M[QuickSight\nPopulation Dashboards]
[0m[49m[39m  161, 161[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  162, 162[0m:[39m[49m     style A fill:#f9f,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[39m  163, 163[0m:[39m[49m     style D fill:#ff9,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[39m  164, 164[0m:[39m[49m     style I fill:#9ff,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[39m  165, 165[0m:[39m[49m     style F fill:#f9f,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[39m  166, 166[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  167, 167[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  168, 168[0m:[39m[49m ### Prerequisites
[0m[49m[39m  169, 169[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  170, 170[0m:[39m[49m | Requirement | Details |
[0m[49m[39m  171, 171[0m:[39m[49m |-------------|---------|
[0m[49m[39m  172, 172[0m:[39m[49m | **AWS Services** | Amazon SageMaker, Amazon S3, AWS Glue, Amazon DynamoDB, AWS Lambda, Amazon EventBridge, Amazon SNS, Amazon QuickSight |
[0m[49m[39m  173, 173[0m:[39m[49m | **IAM Permissions** | `sagemaker:CreateTransformJob`, `s3:GetObject`, `s3:PutObject`, `glue:StartJobRun`, `dynamodb:PutItem`, `dynamodb:GetItem`, `events:PutEvents`, `sns:Publish` |
[0m[49m[39m  174, 174[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  175, 175[0m:[39m[49m <!-- TODO (TechWriter): Expert review S3 (MEDIUM). Add note: each pipeline phase should use a dedicated IAM role scoped to specific resource ARNs. Glue feature assembly role gets S3 read on source + write on feature store only. SageMaker role gets S3 read on features + write on score history only. Lambda detection role gets DynamoDB write on risk state table + events:PutEvents on specific event bus. Never use a single role with all permissions. -->
[0m[49m[39m  176, 176[0m:[39m[49m | **BAA** | AWS BAA signed (risk scores derived from PHI) |
[0m[49m[39m  177, 177[0m:[39m[49m | **Encryption** | S3: SSE-KMS for all buckets; DynamoDB: encryption at rest (default); all API calls over TLS; Glue jobs: security configuration with S3 and CloudWatch encryption |
[0m[49m[39m  178, 178[0m:[39m[49m | **VPC** | Production: Glue jobs and SageMaker in VPC with VPC endpoints for S3, DynamoDB, CloudWatch Logs, EventBridge, SNS, and SageMaker API. If Lambda detection function runs in VPC, ensure all AWS service calls have corresponding VPC endpoints to avoid NAT Gateway dependency. |
[0m[49m[39m  179, 179[0m:[39m[49m | **CloudTrail** | Enabled: log all SageMaker, Glue, and DynamoDB API calls for HIPAA audit trail |
[0m[49m[39m  180, 180[0m:[39m[49m | **Data Sources** | EHR extract (diagnoses, labs, medications, encounters), claims feed (utilization history), ADT feed (admissions, discharges). Minimum 18-24 months of history for meaningful trajectory analysis. |
[0m[49m[39m  181, 181[0m:[39m[49m | **Cost Estimate** | Glue: ~$0.44/DPU-hour (feature assembly + trajectory computation ~2-4 DPU-hours per run for 500K patients). SageMaker batch transform: ~$0.05/hour for ml.m5.xlarge (scoring 500K patients takes ~30 min). S3 storage: ~$0.023/GB/month. DynamoDB: on-demand pricing, ~$1.25 per million writes. Total: ~$50-150 per monthly scoring cycle for a 500K-member population. |
[0m[49m[39m  182, 182[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  183, 183[0m:[39m[49m ### Ingredients
[0m[49m[39m  184, 184[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  185, 185[0m:[39m[49m | AWS Service | Role |
[0m[49m[39m  186, 186[0m:[39m[49m |------------|------|
[0m[49m[39m  187, 187[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon SageMaker** | Trains risk models; runs batch scoring on full population each cycle |
[0m[49m[39m  188, 188[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon S3** | Stores feature matrices, score history (longitudinal), and trajectory results |
[0m[49m[39m  189, 189[0m:[39m[49m | **AWS Glue** | Assembles features from source systems; computes trajectory metrics across scoring cycles |
[0m[49m[39m  190, 190[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon DynamoDB** | Stores current patient risk state for real-time care management lookups |
[0m[49m[39m  191, 191[0m:[39m[49m | **AWS Lambda** | Applies rising risk detection rules; prioritizes and routes flagged patients |
[0m[49m[39m  192, 192[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon EventBridge** | Schedules pipeline execution; routes alert events to downstream systems |
[0m[49m[39m  193, 193[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon SNS** | Delivers notifications to care management teams for newly flagged patients |
[0m[49m[39m  194, 194[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon QuickSight** | Population-level dashboards for leadership visibility into rising risk trends |
[0m[49m[39m  195, 195[0m:[39m[49m | **AWS KMS** | Manages encryption keys for all data stores |
[0m[49m[39m  196, 196[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  197, 197[0m:[39m[49m ### Code
[0m[49m[39m  198, 198[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  199, 199[0m:[39m[49m #### Walkthrough
[0m[49m[39m  200, 200[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  201, 201[0m:[39m[49m **Step 1: Feature assembly from source systems.** On each scoring cycle, pull the relevant clinical and utilization data for the entire managed population. This includes current diagnoses, recent lab results, medication lists, encounter history, and prior utilization. The feature set should match what the risk model was trained on, plus additional temporal features (days since last visit, number of encounters in trailing windows). This step is the most time-consuming because it involves joining data from multiple source systems, handling missing values, and applying the same transformations used during model training. Skip this step or get the transformations wrong, and your scores will be meaningless or worse, systematically biased.
[0m[49m[39m  202, 202[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  203, 203[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  204, 204[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION assemble_features(population_list, scoring_date):
[0m[49m[39m  205, 205[0m:[39m[49m     // Pull data for all patients in the managed population as of the scoring date.
[0m[49m[39m  206, 206[0m:[39m[49m     // Each source system provides a different slice of the patient's clinical picture.
[0m[49m[39m  207, 207[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  208, 208[0m:[39m[49m     features = empty table with one row per patient
[0m[49m[39m  209, 209[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  210, 210[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each patient_id in population_list:
[0m[49m[39m  211, 211[0m:[39m[49m         // Clinical data: active diagnoses, recent labs, current medications
[0m[49m[39m  212, 212[0m:[39m[49m         clinical = query EHR extract for patient_id:
[0m[49m[39m  213, 213[0m:[39m[49m             - active_diagnoses (ICD-10 codes with onset dates)
[0m[49m[39m  214, 214[0m:[39m[49m             - lab_results (last 12 months, most recent value per test)
[0m[49m[39m  215, 215[0m:[39m[49m             - medications (active prescriptions with start dates)
[0m[49m[39m  216, 216[0m:[39m[49m             - vitals (most recent set)
[0m[49m[39m  217, 217[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  218, 218[0m:[39m[49m         // Utilization history: encounters, admissions, ED visits in trailing windows
[0m[49m[39m  219, 219[0m:[39m[49m         utilization = query claims/encounter data for patient_id:
[0m[49m[39m  220, 220[0m:[39m[49m             - inpatient_admissions_3mo, _6mo, _12mo (counts)
[0m[49m[39m  221, 221[0m:[39m[49m             - ed_visits_3mo, _6mo, _12mo (counts)
[0m[49m[39m  222, 222[0m:[39m[49m             - specialist_visits_3mo, _6mo, _12mo (counts)
[0m[49m[39m  223, 223[0m:[39m[49m             - total_cost_3mo, _6mo, _12mo (allowed amounts)
[0m[49m[39m  224, 224[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  225, 225[0m:[39m[49m         // Engagement indicators: gaps in care, missed appointments
[0m[49m[39m  226, 226[0m:[39m[49m         engagement = query scheduling/ADT data for patient_id:
[0m[49m[39m  227, 227[0m:[39m[49m             - days_since_last_pcp_visit
[0m[49m[39m  228, 228[0m:[39m[49m             - missed_appointments_6mo (count)
[0m[49m[39m  229, 229[0m:[39m[49m             - medication_refill_gap_days (average across active meds)
[0m[49m[39m  230, 230[0m:[39m[49m             - days_since_last_lab_draw
[0m[49m[39m  231, 231[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  232, 232[0m:[39m[49m         // Combine into a single feature vector for this patient
[0m[49m[39m  233, 233[0m:[39m[49m         features[patient_id] = merge(clinical, utilization, engagement)
[0m[49m[39m  234, 234[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  235, 235[0m:[39m[49m     // Apply standard transformations: encode categoricals, impute missing values,
[0m[49m[39m  236, 236[0m:[39m[49m     // normalize continuous features. Use the SAME transformer fitted during training.
[0m[49m[39m  237, 237[0m:[39m[49m     features = apply_trained_transformations(features)
[0m[49m[39m  238, 238[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  239, 239[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN features
[0m[49m[39m  240, 240[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  241, 241[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  242, 242[0m:[39m[49m **Step 2: Batch risk scoring.** Pass the assembled feature matrix through the trained risk model to produce a risk score for every patient in the population. This is a batch operation: you're scoring hundreds of thousands of patients in a single job, not one at a time. The output is a score (typically a probability or a relative risk index) for each patient, timestamped with the current scoring cycle. These scores will be appended to the longitudinal history, not overwritten. Every historical score is retained because trajectory computation needs the full time series.
[0m[49m[39m  243, 243[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  244, 244[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  245, 245[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION score_population(feature_matrix, model_endpoint, scoring_date):
[0m[49m[39m  246, 246[0m:[39m[49m     // Submit the full feature matrix to the model for batch scoring.
[0m[49m[39m  247, 247[0m:[39m[49m     // The model returns one risk score per patient.
[0m[49m[39m  248, 248[0m:[39m[49m     // For a 500K-patient population, this typically takes 15-30 minutes on a single instance.
[0m[49m[39m  249, 249[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  250, 250[0m:[39m[49m     scores = call batch_transform(
[0m[49m[39m  251, 251[0m:[39m[49m         model       = model_endpoint,       // the trained risk model (e.g., XGBoost)
[0m[49m[39m  252, 252[0m:[39m[49m         input_data  = feature_matrix,       // all patients' feature vectors
[0m[49m[39m  253, 253[0m:[39m[49m         output_path = "s3://scores/{scoring_date}/"  // where to write results
[0m[49m[39m  254, 254[0m:[39m[49m     )
[0m[49m[39m  255, 255[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  256, 256[0m:[39m[49m     // Structure the output: patient_id, score, scoring_date
[0m[49m[39m  257, 257[0m:[39m[49m     // This format enables easy appending to the longitudinal score history.
[0m[49m[39m  258, 258[0m:[39m[49m     scored_records = empty list
[0m[49m[39m  259, 259[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each patient_id, score in scores:
[0m[49m[39m  260, 260[0m:[39m[49m         append to scored_records: {
[0m[49m[39m  261, 261[0m:[39m[49m             patient_id:   patient_id,
[0m[49m[39m  262, 262[0m:[39m[49m             risk_score:   score,              // 0.0 to 1.0 probability or relative index
[0m[49m[39m  263, 263[0m:[39m[49m             scoring_date: scoring_date,       // when this score was computed
[0m[49m[39m  264, 264[0m:[39m[49m             model_version: model_endpoint.version  // track which model produced this score
[0m[49m[39m  265, 265[0m:[39m[49m         }
[0m[49m[39m  266, 266[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  267, 267[0m:[39m[49m     // Append (not overwrite) to the longitudinal score history in S3.
[0m[49m[39m  268, 268[0m:[39m[49m     // Partition by scoring_date for efficient time-range queries.
[0m[49m[39m  269, 269[0m:[39m[49m     append scored_records to "s3://score-history/date={scoring_date}/"
[0m[49m[39m  270, 270[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  271, 271[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN scored_records
[0m[49m[39m  272, 272[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  273, 273[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  274, 274[0m:[39m[49m **Step 3: Trajectory computation.** This is the core of rising risk detection. For each patient, retrieve their full score history and compute trajectory metrics: slope over multiple time windows, absolute and relative deltas, acceleration (change in slope), and percentile position. The multi-window approach is important because it captures both rapid deterioration (3-month spike) and slow drift (12-month gradual increase). A patient might have a flat 3-month trajectory but a clearly rising 12-month trajectory, or vice versa. Both patterns are clinically meaningful but suggest different intervention urgencies.
[0m[49m[39m  275, 275[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  276, 276[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  277, 277[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION compute_trajectories(current_scores, score_history):
[0m[49m[39m  278, 278[0m:[39m[49m     // For each patient, compute trajectory metrics using their full score history.
[0m[49m[39m  279, 279[0m:[39m[49m     // This is embarrassingly parallel: each patient's computation is independent.
[0m[49m[39m  280, 280[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  281, 281[0m:[39m[49m     trajectories = empty list
[0m[49m[39m  282, 282[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  283, 283[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each patient in current_scores:
[0m[49m[39m  284, 284[0m:[39m[49m         // Retrieve this patient's historical scores, ordered by date
[0m[49m[39m  285, 285[0m:[39m[49m         history = query score_history WHERE patient_id = patient.patient_id
[0m[49m[39m  286, 286[0m:[39m[49m                   ORDER BY scoring_date ASC
[0m[49m[39m  287, 287[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  288, 288[0m:[39m[49m         // IMPORTANT: Only compute slopes using scores from the same model version.
[0m[49m[39m  289, 289[0m:[39m[49m         // If model_version changed during the history window, either:
[0m[49m[39m  290, 290[0m:[39m[49m         // (a) re-score historical periods with the current model, or
[0m[49m[39m  291, 291[0m:[39m[49m         // (b) compute slope only from scores produced by the current model version,
[0m[49m[39m  292, 292[0m:[39m[49m         //     accepting a shorter effective history window after each model update.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      293[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         history = filter history WHERE model_version = current_model_version
[0m[49m[39m  293, 294[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  294, 295[0m:[39m[49m         // Need at least 3 data points for meaningful trajectory analysis.
[0m[49m[39m  295, 296[0m:[39m[49m         // Patients with fewer points get flagged as "insufficient history."
[0m[49m[39m  296, 297[0m:[39m[49m         IF length(history) < 3:
[0m[49m[39m  297, 298[0m:[39m[49m             append to trajectories: {
[0m[49m[39m  298, 299[0m:[39m[49m                 patient_id: patient.patient_id,
[0m[49m[39m  299, 300[0m:[39m[49m                 status: "INSUFFICIENT_HISTORY",
[0m[49m[39m  300, 301[0m:[39m[49m                 current_score: patient.risk_score
[0m[49m[39m  301, 302[0m:[39m[49m             }
[0m[49m[39m  302, 303[0m:[39m[49m             CONTINUE
[0m[49m[39m  303, 304[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  304, 305[0m:[39m[49m         // Compute slope over multiple windows using linear regression.
[0m[49m[39m  305, 306[0m:[39m[49m         // Slope = rate of change in risk score per month.
[0m[49m[39m  306, 307[0m:[39m[49m         slope_3mo  = linear_regression_slope(history, window = last 3 months)
[0m[49m[39m  307, 308[0m:[39m[49m         slope_6mo  = linear_regression_slope(history, window = last 6 months)
[0m[49m[39m  308, 309[0m:[39m[49m         slope_12mo = linear_regression_slope(history, window = last 12 months)
[0m[49m[39m  309, 310[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  310, 311[0m:[39m[49m         // Compute absolute and relative deltas
[0m[49m[39m  311, 312[0m:[39m[49m         score_3mo_ago  = get_score_at(history, months_ago = 3)
[0m[49m[39m  312, 313[0m:[39m[49m         score_6mo_ago  = get_score_at(history, months_ago = 6)
[0m[49m[39m  313, 314[0m:[39m[49m         score_12mo_ago = get_score_at(history, months_ago = 12)
[0m[49m[39m  314, 315[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  315, 316[0m:[39m[49m         delta_3mo  = patient.risk_score - score_3mo_ago   // absolute change
[0m[49m[39m  316, 317[0m:[39m[49m         delta_6mo  = patient.risk_score - score_6mo_ago
[0m[49m[39m  317, 318[0m:[39m[49m         delta_12mo = patient.risk_score - score_12mo_ago
[0m[49m[39m  318, 319[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  319, 320[0m:[39m[49m         relative_delta_6mo = delta_6mo / score_6mo_ago IF score_6mo_ago > 0 ELSE 0
[0m[49m[39m  320, 321[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  321, 322[0m:[39m[49m         // Compute acceleration: is the rate of change itself increasing?
[0m[49m[39m  322, 323[0m:[39m[49m         // Positive acceleration means deterioration is speeding up.
[0m[49m[39m  323, 324[0m:[39m[49m         acceleration = slope_3mo - slope_6mo  // if 3mo slope > 6mo slope, accelerating
[0m[49m[39m  324, 325[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  325, 326[0m:[39m[49m         // Compute percentile position in current population
[0m[49m[39m  326, 327[0m:[39m[49m         percentile = rank of patient.risk_score within current_scores (0-100)
[0m[49m[39m  327, 328[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  328, 329[0m:[39m[49m         append to trajectories: {
[0m[49m[39m  329, 330[0m:[39m[49m             patient_id:       patient.patient_id,
[0m[49m[39m  330, 331[0m:[39m[49m             current_score:    patient.risk_score,
[0m[49m[39m  331, 332[0m:[39m[49m             percentile:       percentile,
[0m[49m[39m  332, 333[0m:[39m[49m             slope_3mo:        slope_3mo,
[0m[49m[39m  333, 334[0m:[39m[49m             slope_6mo:        slope_6mo,
[0m[49m[39m  334, 335[0m:[39m[49m             slope_12mo:       slope_12mo,
[0m[49m[39m  335, 336[0m:[39m[49m             delta_3mo:        delta_3mo,
[0m[49m[39m  336, 337[0m:[39m[49m             delta_6mo:        delta_6mo,
[0m[49m[39m  337, 338[0m:[39m[49m             delta_12mo:       delta_12mo,
[0m[49m[39m  338, 339[0m:[39m[49m             relative_delta_6mo: relative_delta_6mo,
[0m[49m[39m  339, 340[0m:[39m[49m             acceleration:     acceleration,
[0m[49m[39m  340, 341[0m:[39m[49m             data_points:      length(history),
[0m[49m[39m  341, 342[0m:[39m[49m             status:           "COMPUTED"
[0m[49m[39m  342, 343[0m:[39m[49m         }
[0m[49m[39m  343, 344[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  344, 345[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN trajectories
[0m[49m[39m  345, 346[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  346, 347[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  347, 348[0m:[39m[49m **Step 4: Rising risk detection and classification.** Apply detection rules to the trajectory metrics to identify patients whose risk is meaningfully increasing. The rules combine multiple signals to reduce false positives: a single elevated metric might be noise, but multiple converging indicators suggest genuine deterioration. The output is a classified list: patients flagged as "rising risk" with a severity tier and the specific signals that triggered the flag. This transparency is critical for care managers, who need to understand why a patient was flagged before they can design an appropriate intervention.
[0m[49m[39m  348, 349[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  349, 350[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  350, 351[0m:[39m[49m // Detection thresholds. These should be calibrated to your population and intervention capacity.
[0m[49m[39m  351, 352[0m:[39m[49m // Start conservative (fewer flags, higher confidence) and loosen as you validate.
[0m[49m[39m  352, 353[0m:[39m[49m THRESHOLDS = {
[0m[49m[39m  353, 354[0m:[39m[49m     slope_6mo_high:       0.05,    // risk score increasing by 0.05+ per month over 6 months
[0m[49m[39m  354, 355[0m:[39m[49m     slope_6mo_moderate:   0.02,    // moderate increase
[0m[49m[39m  355, 356[0m:[39m[49m     delta_6mo_high:       0.20,    // absolute score increase of 0.20+ over 6 months
[0m[49m[39m  356, 357[0m:[39m[49m     delta_6mo_moderate:   0.10,    // moderate absolute increase
[0m[49m[39m  357, 358[0m:[39m[49m     relative_delta_high:  0.50,    // 50%+ relative increase over 6 months
[0m[49m[39m  358, 359[0m:[39m[49m     acceleration_high:    0.02,    // slope itself is increasing by 0.02+ per month
[0m[49m[39m  359, 360[0m:[39m[49m     min_current_score:    0.15,    // don't flag patients with very low absolute risk
[0m[49m[39m  360, 361[0m:[39m[49m     max_current_score:    0.75     // patients above this are already "high risk," not "rising"
[0m[49m[39m  361, 362[0m:[39m[49m }
[0m[49m[39m  362, 363[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  363, 364[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION detect_rising_risk(trajectories):
[0m[49m[39m  364, 365[0m:[39m[49m     flagged = empty list
[0m[49m[39m  365, 366[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  366, 367[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each patient in trajectories:
[0m[49m[39m  367, 368[0m:[39m[49m         IF patient.status != "COMPUTED":
[0m[49m[39m  368, 369[0m:[39m[49m             CONTINUE
[0m[49m[39m  369, 370[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  370, 371[0m:[39m[49m         // Guard: only flag patients in the "rising" zone.
[0m[49m[39m  371, 372[0m:[39m[49m         // Below min_current_score: too low to warrant intervention even if rising.
[0m[49m[39m  372, 373[0m:[39m[49m         // Above max_current_score: already high-risk, should be in existing programs.
[0m[49m[39m  373, 374[0m:[39m[49m         IF patient.current_score < THRESHOLDS.min_current_score:
[0m[49m[39m  374, 375[0m:[39m[49m             CONTINUE
[0m[49m[39m  375, 376[0m:[39m[49m         IF patient.current_score > THRESHOLDS.max_current_score:
[0m[49m[39m  376, 377[0m:[39m[49m             CONTINUE
[0m[49m[39m  377, 378[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  378, 379[0m:[39m[49m         // Collect triggered signals
[0m[49m[39m  379, 380[0m:[39m[49m         signals = empty list
[0m[49m[39m  380, 381[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  381, 382[0m:[39m[49m         IF patient.slope_6mo >= THRESHOLDS.slope_6mo_high:
[0m[49m[39m  382, 383[0m:[39m[49m             append "HIGH_SLOPE_6MO" to signals
[0m[49m[39m  383, 384[0m:[39m[49m         ELSE IF patient.slope_6mo >= THRESHOLDS.slope_6mo_moderate:
[0m[49m[39m  384, 385[0m:[39m[49m             append "MODERATE_SLOPE_6MO" to signals
[0m[49m[39m  385, 386[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  386, 387[0m:[39m[49m         IF patient.delta_6mo >= THRESHOLDS.delta_6mo_high:
[0m[49m[39m  387, 388[0m:[39m[49m             append "HIGH_DELTA_6MO" to signals
[0m[49m[39m  388, 389[0m:[39m[49m         ELSE IF patient.delta_6mo >= THRESHOLDS.delta_6mo_moderate:
[0m[49m[39m  389, 390[0m:[39m[49m             append "MODERATE_DELTA_6MO" to signals
[0m[49m[39m  390, 391[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  391, 392[0m:[39m[49m         IF patient.relative_delta_6mo >= THRESHOLDS.relative_delta_high:
[0m[49m[39m  392, 393[0m:[39m[49m             append "HIGH_RELATIVE_CHANGE" to signals
[0m[49m[39m  393, 394[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  394, 395[0m:[39m[49m         IF patient.acceleration >= THRESHOLDS.acceleration_high:
[0m[49m[39m  395, 396[0m:[39m[49m             append "ACCELERATING" to signals
[0m[49m[39m  396, 397[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  397, 398[0m:[39m[49m         // Require at least 2 converging signals to flag.
[0m[49m[39m  398, 399[0m:[39m[49m         // Single-signal flags have too many false positives.
[0m[49m[39m  399, 400[0m:[39m[49m         IF length(signals) >= 2:
[0m[49m[39m  400, 401[0m:[39m[49m             // Assign severity tier based on signal strength
[0m[49m[39m  401, 402[0m:[39m[49m             severity = "HIGH" IF any signal contains "HIGH" ELSE "MODERATE"
[0m[49m[39m  402, 403[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  403, 404[0m:[39m[49m             append to flagged: {
[0m[49m[39m  404, 405[0m:[39m[49m                 patient_id:     patient.patient_id,
[0m[49m[39m  405, 406[0m:[39m[49m                 current_score:  patient.current_score,
[0m[49m[39m  406, 407[0m:[39m[49m                 percentile:     patient.percentile,
[0m[49m[39m  407, 408[0m:[39m[49m                 severity:       severity,
[0m[49m[39m  408, 409[0m:[39m[49m                 signals:        signals,
[0m[49m[39m  409, 410[0m:[39m[49m                 slope_6mo:      patient.slope_6mo,
[0m[49m[39m  410, 411[0m:[39m[49m                 delta_6mo:      patient.delta_6mo,
[0m[49m[39m  411, 412[0m:[39m[49m                 acceleration:   patient.acceleration,
[0m[49m[39m  412, 413[0m:[39m[49m                 flagged_date:   current_date()
[0m[49m[39m  413, 414[0m:[39m[49m             }
[0m[49m[39m  414, 415[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  415, 416[0m:[39m[49m     // Sort by severity (HIGH first), then by slope (steepest first)
[0m[49m[39m  416, 417[0m:[39m[49m     sort flagged by severity DESC, slope_6mo DESC
[0m[49m[39m  417, 418[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  418, 419[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN flagged
[0m[49m[39m  419, 420[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  420, 421[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  421, 422[0m:[39m[49m **Step 5: Store results and route to care management.** Write the rising risk flags to the operational database so care management platforms can access them in real-time. Also emit events for newly flagged patients so care managers receive notifications. The routing logic determines which care management program is most appropriate based on the nature of the risk increase (e.g., behavioral health escalation vs. chronic disease management vs. social needs). Include the trajectory summary in the notification so the care manager has context without needing to look it up separately.
[0m[49m[39m  422, 423[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  423, 424[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  424, 425[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION store_and_route(flagged_patients, previous_flags):
[0m[49m[39m  425, 426[0m:[39m[49m     // Identify newly flagged patients (not flagged in the previous cycle).
[0m[49m[39m  426, 427[0m:[39m[49m     // Only send notifications for new flags to avoid alert fatigue.
[0m[49m[39m  427, 428[0m:[39m[49m     previously_flagged_ids = set of patient_ids from previous_flags
[0m[49m[39m  428, 429[0m:[39m[49m     newly_flagged = filter flagged_patients WHERE patient_id NOT IN previously_flagged_ids
[0m[49m[39m  429, 430[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  430, 431[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each patient in flagged_patients:
[0m[49m[39m  431, 432[0m:[39m[49m         // Write/update the patient's risk state in the operational database.
[0m[49m[39m  432, 433[0m:[39m[49m         // Care management platforms query this for real-time risk context.
[0m[49m[39m  433, 434[0m:[39m[49m         write to database table "patient-risk-state":
[0m[49m[39m  434, 435[0m:[39m[49m             patient_id      = patient.patient_id
[0m[49m[39m  435, 436[0m:[39m[49m             risk_tier       = "RISING"
[0m[49m[39m  436, 437[0m:[39m[49m             severity        = patient.severity
[0m[49m[39m  437, 438[0m:[39m[49m             current_score   = patient.current_score
[0m[49m[39m  438, 439[0m:[39m[49m             trajectory_slope = patient.slope_6mo
[0m[49m[39m  439, 440[0m:[39m[49m             signals         = patient.signals
[0m[49m[39m  440, 441[0m:[39m[49m             flagged_date    = patient.flagged_date
[0m[49m[39m  441, 442[0m:[39m[49m             last_updated    = current_timestamp()
[0m[49m[39m  442, 443[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  443, 444[0m:[39m[49m     // Emit events for newly flagged patients only
[0m[49m[39m  444, 445[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each patient in newly_flagged:
[0m[49m[39m  445, 446[0m:[39m[49m         // Determine routing based on primary signal pattern
[0m[49m[39m  446, 447[0m:[39m[49m         program = determine_program(patient.signals, patient.current_score)
[0m[49m[39m  447, 448[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  448, 449[0m:[39m[49m         emit event:
[0m[49m[39m  449, 450[0m:[39m[49m             type:        "RISING_RISK_IDENTIFIED"
[0m[49m[39m  450, 451[0m:[39m[49m             patient_id:  patient.patient_id
[0m[49m[39m  451, 452[0m:[39m[49m             severity:    patient.severity
[0m[49m[39m  452, 453[0m:[39m[49m             program:     program          // e.g., "CHRONIC_DISEASE_MGMT", "BH_ESCALATION"
[0m[49m[39m  453, 454[0m:[39m[49m             signals:     patient.signals
[0m[49m[39m  454, 455[0m:[39m[49m             slope_6mo:   patient.slope_6mo
[0m[49m[39m  455, 456[0m:[39m[49m             message:     "Patient risk score has increased by {delta_6mo} over 6 months. "
[0m[49m[39m  456, 457[0m:[39m[49m                          "Current score: {current_score} (percentile: {percentile}). "
[0m[49m[39m  457, 458[0m:[39m[49m                          "Trajectory: {severity} rising risk with signals: {signals}."
[0m[49m[39m  458, 459[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  459, 460[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN {
[0m[49m[39m  460, 461[0m:[39m[49m         total_flagged:  length(flagged_patients),
[0m[49m[39m  461, 462[0m:[39m[49m         newly_flagged:  length(newly_flagged),
[0m[49m[39m  462, 463[0m:[39m[49m         high_severity:  count WHERE severity == "HIGH",
[0m[49m[39m  463, 464[0m:[39m[49m         moderate_severity: count WHERE severity == "MODERATE"
[0m[49m[39m  464, 465[0m:[39m[49m     }
[0m[49m[39m  465, 466[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  466, 467[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  467, 468[0m:[39m[49m > **Curious how this looks in Python?** The pseudocode above covers the concepts. If you'd like to see sample Python code that demonstrates these patterns using boto3, check out the [Python Example](chapter07.06-python-example). It walks through each step with inline comments and notes on what you'd need to change for a real deployment.
[0m[49m[39m  468, 469[0m:[39m[49m 
